  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 5.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "To repair",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The idea of this verb (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "חָזַק",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") is that of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "making strong. From year to year",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "making strong. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "cmt_word",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "From year to year",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The compound adverbial expression ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "חָדֵּי",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", here used for \"from,\" era-braces the idea of\" unfailingly from year to year.\" The command given here to the priests and Levites is expressed very differently, though in no degree contadictorily, in the parallel (see its vers. 4, 5). The addition is there found, \"every man of his acquaintance;\" this expression may glance at the very supposable circumstance that the priest and Levite collecting deputations would naturally go respectively to the towns and cities where they had been located beforetime. A slight ambiguity is perhaps occasioned by the impression that the fourth verse (in the parallel) produces - that the priests and Levites should wait to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "receive, e.g.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in Jerusalem. This, however, is sot what is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "said",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and need not, therefore, be made into a difficulty. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Howbeit the Levites hastened not.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " We are not told ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "why",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " this delay was, nor does the subsequent narrative seem to elucidate it, further than this - that the delay somehow seemed to rest with Jehoiada, as the king appealed to him for explanation. 2 Chronicles 24:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
